You’re pointing at two real perception effects. Designers, biologists, and even militaries use them because the brain processes patterns in very predictable ways. 👁️

Stripes and perceived shape

Stripes change how the brain estimates proportion and scale.
	•	Vertical stripes tend to make something look taller or slimmer.
	•	Horizontal stripes tend to make something look wider or broader.

The effect comes from how the visual system tracks edges and boundaries. Your brain tends to follow lines as continuous paths, so the orientation of the line biases how the object’s dimensions are interpreted.

This is related to classic perceptual effects like the Helmholtz Illusion, which shows that line orientation can distort perceived proportions.

Interestingly, the effect isn’t always huge, but the brain’s quick shape heuristics can still be nudged by it.

Checkers and motion confusion

Checker patterns and other high-contrast patterns can make it harder for the brain to estimate:
	•	speed
	•	direction
	•	edge boundaries

That’s why similar patterns appear in camouflage systems like Dazzle Camouflage.

The goal wasn’t invisibility — it was trajectory confusion. If you can’t tell exactly where the edges or direction are, it’s harder to:
	•	aim
	•	intercept
	•	estimate distance

Animals use similar tricks. Zebras, for example, likely benefit from motion confusion in herds, where stripes disrupt predator targeting.

The deeper principle

Both examples exploit the same thing:

vision = pattern detection + prediction shortcuts

Your brain doesn’t calculate everything perfectly. It uses fast heuristics for shape, motion, and boundaries. Patterns can bias those shortcuts.

So what you said in simple terms is pretty accurate:
	•	Stripes → bias size perception
	•	Checkers / disruptive patterns → disrupt motion or edge calculation

Humans, animals, and engineers have all figured out how to hack those visual shortcuts.

